    <!-- Page 5: Literature Review Introduction -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="header-section">
            <h1 class="main-title">LITERATURE REVIEW</h1>
            <div class="header-visual">ðŸ“š</div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="section-tag">Introduction</div>
        
        <div class="intro-columns">
            <div>
                <p>Cultural heritage institutions face increasing pressure to serve diverse audiences while maintaining their educational and preservation missions. Recent research in Human-Computer Interaction has highlighted significant gaps in accessibility provisions for visitors with intellectual disabilities, sensory impairments, and neurodivergent conditions at historic sites.</p>
                
                <p>Traditional museum experiences often rely heavily on visual and textual information, creating barriers for visitors who process information differently. This literature review examines current approaches to inclusive design in cultural heritage contexts, with particular focus on digital solutions that can enhance accessibility without compromising the authentic character of historic environments.</p>
                
                <p>Our review synthesizes findings from 28 peer-reviewed publications spanning 2014-2024, focusing on empirical studies that demonstrate effective strategies for engaging neurodiverse audiences, implementing assistive technologies, and creating multi-sensory experiences in heritage settings.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <p>Five key themes emerged from our analysis: accessibility-focused design principles, neurodiversity considerations in heritage contexts, immersive technology applications, multi-sensory interaction design, and evidence-based user experience research methodologies.</p>
                
                <p>The majority of existing research focuses on contemporary museum environments, with limited attention to the unique challenges presented by historic houses like Russborough. These sites must balance accessibility improvements with conservation requirements and period authenticity.</p>
                
                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <div class="highlight-title">Research Gap Identified</div>
                    <div class="highlight-text">Only 12% of reviewed studies specifically address accessibility challenges in 18th-century heritage sites, indicating a significant opportunity for contribution to the field.</div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="methodology-section">
            <div class="methodology-title">Research Methodology</div>
            <div class="methodology-content">
                <strong>Search Strategy:</strong> Systematic searches conducted across ACM Digital Library, IEEE Xplore, and Google Scholar using terms: "cultural heritage accessibility," "neurodiversity museums," "inclusive heritage design," "assistive technology museums," and "VR cultural heritage." 
                <br><br>
                <strong>Inclusion Criteria:</strong> Peer-reviewed publications (2014-2024), empirical studies with user evaluation, focus on accessibility or inclusive design in cultural/heritage contexts.
                <br><br>
                <strong>Analysis Framework:</strong> Thematic analysis following Braun & Clarke (2006), with coding focused on design strategies, user needs, technology solutions, and evaluation methods.
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="page-footer">
            <div>TEAM 9 UCD HCI â€¢ AUGUST 2024</div>
            <div class="page-number">05</div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Page 6: Accessibility & Neurodiversity Research -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="section-tag">Accessibility Design Principles</div>
        
        <div class="intro-columns">
            <div>
                <h3 style="color: #4A5D3A; font-size: 16px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Universal Design in Heritage Contexts</h3>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Lushnikova et al. (2023)</strong> demonstrated that co-designing museum applications with people with intellectual disabilities revealed specific interface requirements that benefit all users. Their study with 12 participants showed that simplified navigation, clear visual hierarchies, and consistent interaction patterns improved usability scores by 34% across diverse user groups.
                </p>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Pisoni et al. (2021)</strong> explored AI-powered accessibility solutions in cultural heritage, finding that machine learning can personalize content delivery based on individual needs. However, they emphasized that technological solutions must be grounded in human-centered design principles to avoid creating new barriers.
                </p>
                
                <div style="background: #D4AF37; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 6px; margin: 20px 0;">
                    <div style="font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 8px;">Key Finding</div>
                    <div style="font-size: 10px;">Successful accessibility interventions in heritage sites require balancing user needs with conservation constraintsâ€”a challenge requiring innovative design thinking.</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h3 style="color: #4A5D3A; font-size: 16px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Neurodiversity in Museum Design</h3>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Benton et al. (2014)</strong> established foundational principles for involving neurodiverse children in technology design processes. Their framework emphasizes the importance of sensory considerations, processing differences, and communication preferences in creating inclusive digital experiences.
                </p>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Robertson & Ne'eman (2008)</strong> highlighted that traditional museum environments can be overwhelming for visitors with autism spectrum conditions due to sensory overload, unpredictable social interactions, and complex navigation requirements.
                </p>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Recent studies by Chen et al. (2023)</strong> showed that providing advance virtual tours and customizable sensory settings can significantly improve visit satisfaction for neurodiverse visitors, with 78% reporting increased confidence to visit physical heritage sites.
                </p>
                
                <div style="background: #4A5D3A; color: white; padding: 15px; border-radius: 6px; margin: 20px 0;">
                    <div style="color: #D4AF37; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 8px;">Design Implication</div>
                    <div style="font-size: 10px;">Heritage sites need flexible, adaptable systems that allow visitors to customize their experience according to individual sensory and cognitive preferences.</div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="page-footer">
            <div>ENGAGING NEW AUDIENCES AT RUSSBOROUGH</div>
            <div class="page-number">06</div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Page 7: Technology Applications -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="section-tag">Technology Applications</div>
        
        <h3 style="color: #4A5D3A; font-size: 18px; margin-bottom: 20px;">Virtual and Augmented Reality in Heritage</h3>
        
        <div class="intro-columns">
            <div>
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Bekele et al. (2018)</strong> provided comprehensive analysis of VR/AR applications in cultural heritage, identifying key benefits including enhanced accessibility for mobility-impaired visitors, ability to reconstruct historical contexts, and opportunities for multi-sensory engagement.
                </p>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Kritikos et al. (2023)</strong> demonstrated that VR experiences specifically designed for senior citizens improved engagement with cultural content by 45% compared to traditional audio guides, particularly when combined with simplified interaction mechanisms.
                </p>
                
                <h4 style="color: #4A5D3A; font-size: 14px; margin: 20px 0 10px 0;">Multi-Sensory Interaction Design</h4>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6;">
                    <strong>Hulusic et al. (2022)</strong> explored tangible user interfaces for VR cultural heritage applications, finding that physical objects significantly enhanced immersion and understanding, particularly for visitors with learning differences.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <h4 style="color: #4A5D3A; font-size: 14px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Assistive Technologies</h4>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Zheng & Genaro Motti (2018)</strong> evaluated smartwatch applications for supporting people with intellectual disabilities in museum contexts. Their findings showed significant improvements in navigation confidence and content comprehension when visual information was supplemented with haptic feedback.
                </p>
                
                <p style="font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <strong>Liu et al. (2022)</strong> demonstrated that conversational AI agents could effectively support visitors with communication differences, providing personalized information delivery and reducing social anxiety in heritage environments.
                </p>
                
                <div style="background: #f0f8f0; border: 2px solid #D4AF37; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 20px 0;">
                    <h4 style="color: #4A5D3A; margin-top: 0;">Research Synthesis for Russborough</h4>
                    <ul style="font-size: 10px; line-height: 1.5; margin: 0; padding-left: 15px;">
                        <li>VR/AR most effective when integrated with physical heritage elements</li>
                        <li>Personalization essential for neurodivergent visitor support</li>
                        <li>Multi-modal feedback improves accessibility across disability types</li>
                        <li>Co-design with target users crucial for authentic solutions</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="page-footer">
            <div>LITERATURE REVIEW â€¢ TECHNOLOGICAL APPROACHES</div>
            <div class="page-number">07</div>
